'''Susan Lim''' is a [[Singapore]]an surgeon who performed the first successful [[liver transplant]] in [[Singapore]] in 1990.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.singapore.embassy.gov.au/sing/AHC_IWD2007.html MEDIA RELEASE IWD2007 - Australian High Commission<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>


==Early Life==

Lim was born in Singapore and was educated at [[Singapore Chinese Girls' School]] and [[Raffles Institution]].<ref name=SusanLimSurg>[http://www.susanlimsurgery.com/dr_susan_lim.html Susan Lim Surgery<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{Dead link|date=December 2012}} </ref> In 1974 she was awarded a scholarship under the [[Colombo Plan]] to study medicine at [[Monash University]] in [[Australia]].<ref>http://www.monash.edu.au/alumni/prominent-alumni/susan-lim.html Susan Lim - Prominent Monash Alumna</ref>

==Professional Life==

In 2003 Lim started the biotechnology company '''Stem Cell Technologies'''.<ref>http://www.nus.edu.sg/ilo/news/newsletter0423.html#1</ref> The following year she became a Fellow of [[Trinity College (University of Melbourne)]]. She is the youngest and first Singaporean to receive this honor.<ref name="www2.trinity.unimelb.edu.au">http://www2.trinity.unimelb.edu.au/news/media/2004/20040618.shtml</ref>

Lim established the '''Indiapore Trust''' with her husband Deepak Sharma and her friend Satpal Khattar. The trust issued $50,000 to the Straits Times School Pocket Money Fund, which assists struggling parents to meet their children's school expenses. The trust has also donated a science laboratory to [[Raffles Junior College]] and provided scholarships to underprivileged children in [[Singapore]] and [[India]].<ref name="www2.trinity.unimelb.edu.au"/>

Lim sits on the Global Advisory Council of the '''International Society for Stem Cell Research'''.<ref>http://www.isscr.org/leadership/gac.htm</ref> In April 2011 she gave a presentation at [[TED (conference)|TED]] on [http://blog.ted.com/2011/04/15/transplanting-cells-not-organs-susan-lim-on-ted-com/ Transplanting Cells, Not Organs].

In October 2011 Lim was included in The University of Newcastle's book ''100 Women'', which celebrates the achievements of 100 remarkable and inspirational women, both in Australia and globally. <ref>http://www.monash.edu.au/alumni/find/profiles/prominent-alumni//susan-lim.html</ref><ref>http://weblearn.newcastle.edu.au/100-women/</ref>

==Controversy==

In February 2011 the '''Singapore Medical Council''' (SMC) presented a case to the [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]], in which Lim was accused of overcharging one of her patients. <ref>http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/Singapore/Story/STIStory_638329.html</ref> In August 2012 Lim was convicted, issued a 3-year suspension from practicing, and fined. The patient was a member of the royal family of [[Brunei]] and Lim was required to submit a written promise not to overcharge in the future. Lim appealed her sentence and was allowed to continue practicing, pending the outcome of the appeal. <ref>http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1164541/1/.html</ref><ref>http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/3-year-suspension-susan-lim-rules-smc-20120823</ref>

